=== Overview

Year Two introduces wet-path work including dew and rainwater collection, extended maceration, and controlled putrefaction (the Nigredo in wet processing). These materials involve biological activity — bacteria, moulds, yeasts, and environmental contaminants — that presents hazards distinct from the chemical hazards addressed in E.1 and E.3. This document discloses those hazards specifically and provides the required protocols for managing them.

The biological hazards described here are not exotic or alarming when approached with consistent standard hygiene. Healthy adults encounter comparable microbiological exposure routinely. The following protocols make that exposure explicit and manageable.

=== Dew Collection — Specific Hazards and Controls

Dew collects atmospheric and surface material including fungal spores, pollen, particulate pollutants, bird matter, and insect material. Collection site and season significantly affect biological load.

*Collection site:* Collect only from sites that are clean and uncontaminated by agricultural chemicals, vehicle exhaust, heavy foot traffic, or animal use. A clean lawn, meadow, or garden away from roads is appropriate. Urban rooftops, gutters, and paved surfaces are not appropriate collection sites.

*Time and season:* Collect at first light. Spring and autumn dews are cooler and less biologically active than summer dews. Do not collect following a long dry spell (concentration of surface contaminants) or following storm activity.

*Handling:* Use nitrile gloves. Do not splash into eyes. Do not consume raw dew.

*Processing:* Filter through a clean paper filter before laboratory use. Use promptly or refrigerate below 4°C if not used the same day.

#risk-item(
  "respiratory or systemic exposure to concentrated fungal spores, environmental pathogens, or atmospheric pollutants",
  "collecting dew from contaminated sites (roads, rooftops, areas with animal use), or failure to filter collected dew before laboratory use"
)

#risk-item(
  "elevated biological exposure risk for immunocompromised students",
  "proceeding with dew or rainwater collection without first consulting a physician, where the student has disclosed immunocompromised status in the intake form"
)

=== Rainwater Collection — Specific Hazards and Controls

*First-flush rule:* Discard the first 10–15 minutes of any rainfall. Initial rain carries the highest load of atmospheric particulates, surface contamination, and biological material. This rule is non-negotiable.

*Collection surface:* Collect from a clean surface — glass, glazed ceramic, or food-grade stainless. Do not collect from galvanised, lead-flashed, or tarred roofing.

*Filtration:* Filter all collected rainwater through a clean paper filter before any laboratory use.

*Storage:* Store filtered rainwater in sealed glass containers in a cool, dark location. Use within two weeks, or refrigerate.

#risk-item(
  "chemical and biological contamination of the preparation",
  "collecting rainwater without discarding the first-flush, or collecting from lead-flashed, galvanised, or tarred roofing surfaces"
)

=== Putrefaction Work — Specific Hazards and Controls

Putrefaction is a controlled decomposition process conducted in a sealed vessel over sustained warmth. It supports microbial growth including in some circumstances organisms capable of producing toxic metabolites.

==== Vessel Integrity

Use only undamaged, properly sealed glass vessels. Inspect before each session. A cracked vessel developing internal pressure from fermentation gases can fail without warning.

#risk-item(
  "physical injury from vessel failure under fermentation pressure",
  "using any vessel with visible cracks, chips, or weak points for putrefaction work, or heating a completely sealed rigid vessel without a pressure-relief provision"
)

==== Opening Sealed Vessels

Open slowly, away from the face, in a ventilated space. Allow gas pressure to equalise fully before removing the stopper. Never apply heat to a completely sealed, rigid vessel.

#risk-item(
  "chemical or biological exposure from pressurised vessel contents",
  "opening a sealed putrefaction vessel quickly, toward the face, or in an unventilated space, without first allowing pressure to equalise"
)

==== Odour and Ventilation

Putrefaction produces strong odours — sulfurous, ammoniacal, or strongly organic. These odours are a ventilation cue, not merely an unpleasantness to be endured. Ensure adequate ventilation whenever opening putrefying vessels.

#risk-item(
  "respiratory irritation from concentrated organic decomposition gases",
  "opening putrefying vessels in unventilated enclosed spaces, or continuing to work in a space where putrefaction odour has accumulated without remediation"
)

==== Mould Growth

Visible surface mould growth on plant matter in maceration is expected in some preparations and represents early-stage Nigredo. Manage it consistently:

- Do not handle mouldy materials with bare hands. Use gloves.
- Do not inhale directly over an open vessel containing visible mould growth.
- Students with known mould sensitivity, asthma, or other respiratory conditions: take additional precautions and inform your Guide.
- Extensive mould growth producing coloured spores (blue-green *Penicillium*, black *Aspergillus*) should be noted in the journal and reported to the Guide before the next session.

#risk-item(
  "mould spore inhalation and respiratory sensitisation",
  "handling mouldy preparation materials without gloves, or inhaling directly over open vessels containing visible mould growth — particularly where respiratory sensitivity or immunocompromised status is present"
)

==== Unexpected Fermentation Activity

If a vessel shows unexpected vigorous fermentation — sustained bubbling, visible pressure, rapid colour change, or unusual smell — do not open it until activity subsides. Allow the vessel to equilibrate at room temperature. If activity does not subside within 24 hours, or the vessel shows signs of physical stress, contact your Guide before proceeding.

#risk-item(
  "vessel failure and biological exposure from uncontrolled fermentation pressure",
  "opening a vessel showing signs of vigorous unexpected fermentation before pressure has fully subsided"
)

=== General Hygiene Protocols

These protocols apply throughout all wet-path work:

- Wash hands thoroughly before and after every wet-path session.
- Use dedicated equipment for wet-path biological work, separate from mineral work equipment. Do not cross-contaminate.
- Wash all vessels used in putrefaction or maceration with hot water and biodegradable laboratory detergent. Rinse thoroughly. Air-dry fully before storage.
- Spent putrefied plant material may be composted if it contains no harmful additives. Do not dispose of large quantities of concentrated fermented liquids directly into waterways.
- Log the date, material, condition, and any unusual observations (colour, odour, growth) for every wet-path session.

=== Cross-Reference to E.1 and E.3

Biological safety in wet-path work intersects with the general laboratory safety requirements of E.1. Standard PPE (nitrile gloves, face protection when opening putrefaction vessels) applies throughout. The higher-level PPE requirements of E.3 (respirator, chemical splash goggles) are not required for standard plant putrefaction under normal conditions; students with respiratory sensitivities may choose to use an N95 when opening vessels with heavy mould growth.

=== When to Pause and Consult Your Guide

Contact your Guide and pause wet-path work if:

- You develop an unexpected illness (gastroenteritis, respiratory symptoms, skin reaction) following a wet-path session
- A vessel shows behaviour (extreme pressure, violent unexpected fermentation, unusual colour change) that you cannot account for from the curriculum material
- Your immune status changes during the programme in a way that may affect your response to biological exposure
- You are pregnant or become pregnant during the programme

In any genuine health emergency, contact appropriate medical services directly. Do not wait for a Guide response.

